mind-the-time.author: paul-morris
mind-the-time.description: Keep track of how much time you spend on the web, and where you spend it. A ticker shows (1) time spent at the current site and (2) total time spent on the web today. A summary page shows data for today and recent history.
mind-the-time.name: mind-the-time

preferences.description: How to refresh the data on the summary page, automatically or manually.
preferences.name: refreshPref
preferences.title: Summary Page Refresh Mode:

preferences.description: These are messages that indicate the amount of time spent on the web so far today.
preferences.name: showRemindersPref
preferences.title: Show Reminder Messages?

preferences.description: The number of minutes to be logged between each reminder message.
preferences.name: reminderRatePref
preferences.title: Reminder Message Rate (In Minutes)

preferences.description: How to display reminder messages.  The modal-style messages are harder to ignore and work everywhere. The transient toast-style desktop notifications are less disruptive and work natively on Windows, but require Growl on Mac OS X, and libnotify on Linux.
preferences.name: reminderTypePref
preferences.title: Reminder Message Type:

preferences.description: Enter a list of domains separated by commas to prevent those sites from being logged, and any time spent on them from being counted.  For example: "wordpress.org, addons.mozilla.org, www.ubuntu.com"  There is no need to include the "http://" or "https://" from the URL, but you must include any subdomains (such as "www.") when they are part of the site's address.  The ticker text will be "grayed-out" when visiting sites in this list.
preferences.name: whiteListPref
preferences.title: Exclude These Sites (White List)
